1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:19,880
Hey, nice to meet you. I'm Crawl, and I'll be your instructor for today. Every time you get behind the wheel, you hold lives in your hands. Driving is a massive responsibility, and accidents carry a heavy physical and financial toll. That is why motor insurance is not just a requirement, it is a shield.

2
00:00:19,880 --> 00:00:55,560
Motor insurance covers the ownership, maintenance, and use of a motor vehicle. In the Philippines, the motor car policy is standard. The rules protect you equally whether you drive a private car, a commercial delivery van, a motorcycle, or a public utility vehicle for hire. Your policy provides two main lifelines. First, physical damage insurance protects your vehicle. Second, liability insurance covers the devastating bodily injuries or property damage your car might cause to others.

3
00:00:55,560 --> 00:01:32,400
The foundation of this protection is Section 1, compulsory third-party liability, or CTPL. You cannot register a car without it. It pays up to 100,000 pesos to help a third party in the event of death or bodily injury. To be clear, a third party means the public or employees. For the coverage to apply, the person driving must be an authorized driver with a valid license. If you have a private car or motorcycle, a driving other car clause even extends this protection when you are driving a vehicle you don't own.

4
00:01:32,400 --> 00:02:11,520
But what happens in the chaotic aftermath of a crash? When tragedy strikes, families should not have to endure a lengthy court battle just to pay for emergency hospital care or burial expenses. That is why Section 2, no-fault indemnity exists. It provides immediate compassionate relief up to 15,000 pesos for injury or death without the need to prove who was at fault. To release these funds, the family simply provides basic proof like a police report, medical receipts, or a death certificate.

5
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:22,920
While sections 1 and 2 focus on the human cost, the physical wreckage left behind brings its own stress. Let's turn the page and look at how we pick up the pieces.